<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE KNOW CLOUT WHEN THEY SEE IT; 
</P>
<P>
POLITICS: WITH HIS APPOINTEES AND FRIENDS AT THE CENTER OF THE LINCOLN S&amp;L 
SCANDAL, DEUKMEJIAN CAN'T WASH HIS HANDS OF THE AFFAIR. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAN WALTERS, Dan Walters writes a column for the Sacramento Bee. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As the dust settled from the Oct. 17 earthquake, Gov. George Deukmejian 
appointed a blue-ribbon commission to look into the seismic safety of 
California's freeways. Most of the deaths caused by the quake had occurred when 
a section of Interstate 880 in Oakland collapsed on rush-hour traffic. 
</P>
<P>
A political-financial disaster of comparable proportions surrounds the collapse 
of Lincoln Savings &amp; Loan. An estimated 23,000 Californians lost hundreds 
of millions of dollars that they had unwittingly "invested" in junk bonds 
issued by Lincoln's parent company, American Continental Corp. 
</P>
<P>
The bonds were marketed because state regulators had determined that they were 
backed by a financially sound organization. What those regulators did was 
analogous to what state highway engineers did when they determined that I-880 
could withstand a major earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
Still, the I-880 situation, at worst, was a matter of miscalculation. No one 
has alleged that anyone knowingly erred. 
</P>
<P>
But in the Lincoln matter, just the opposite has become apparent. During the 
months that have elapsed since Lincoln was seized by federal authorities, it's 
become clear that huge amounts of political influence were brought to bear by 
Lincoln, American Continental and their owner, Charles Keating Jr., to stave 
off a close examination of questionable financial practices. And Deukmejian's 
appointees and friends are at the center of the scandal, to wit: 
</P>
<P>
 -- Two state corporations commissioners, Franklin Tom and Christine Bender, 
approved sale of the junk bonds even though suspicions about the financial 
integrity of Lincoln and American Continental already were being voiced by 
lower-level regulators. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Tom and Bender had moved into their regulatory jobs from positions in a law 
firm headed by Deukmejian's friend, political adviser and chief political 
fund-raiser, Karl Samuelian, who recommended them for the appointments. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Samuelian was hired by Keating to lobby for approval of the bond sales, and 
he and Tom personally pressed Bender for a favorable ruling. 
</P>
<P>
 -- As Samuelian joined Keating's vast team of advocates, he began collecting 
tens of thousands of dollars -- some estimates approach $200,000 -- in campaign 
contributions for Deukmejian from Keating and associated firms and individuals. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Deukmejian's savings and loan commissioner at the time, Larry Taggart, 
approved Keating's acquisition of Lincoln. During his last weeks in office in 
1984, Taggart allowed Keating to move $800 million in Lincoln's assets into 
questionable investments, just three days before a federal rule barring such 
investments took effect. He later acknowledged that "I suppose I did that to 
beat the deadline." 
</P>
<P>
 -- When Taggart acted, he already had agreed to become an executive of a 
troubled San Diego investment firm called TCS Financial, headed by Tom Stickel, 
the man who introduced Keating to Samuelian. Within weeks of Taggart's action 
allowing Keating to transfer the money, American Continental pumped nearly $3 
million into TCS, saving it from foundering. 
</P>
<P>
The picture that has emerged from journalistic digging and legislative hearings 
in Washington and Sacramento is that of a regulatory system run amok, more 
concerned with helping Keating prop up his financial empire than with 
protecting the public interest. 
</P>
<P>
Deukmejian has maintained a detached attitude toward the affair, insisting that 
he played no role in what occurred. That really isn't the point. 
</P>
<P>
What is the point is that people he appointed to protect the public from 
unscrupulous financial dealings didn't do their jobs and, from all appearances, 
failed because of personal, political or financial connections to those they 
were supposed to be regulating. 
</P>
<P>
Samuelian says he never went through Deukmejian to serve the interests of 
Keating or any other legal client. 
</P>
<P>
But that isn't the point, either. When Samuelian represents a client before a 
Deukmejian appointee -- and, in this case, one who had worked for him as well 
-- he doesn't have to be explicit. People in such positions aren't stupid. They 
know who Karl Samuelian is and what kind of political clout he represents. 
</P>
<P>
Deukmejian may be concerned about public confidence in the highway system. He 
should be equally concerned about public confidence in the political system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
