<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. JOYCE BROTHERS: SENSIBLE STEPS IN DISCIPLINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOYCE BROTHERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
How to discipline is a source of many family arguments. How much do you know 
about this important subject and how different styles affect children? 
</P>
<P>
Here's a chance to test your views with those of some experts. 
</P>
<P>
QUESTIONS: 
</P>
<P>
1 -- It's not important for parents to agree on styles of discipline. 
</P>
<P>
2 -- Children should never know that a parent is angry with them because it 
erodes their self-esteem and their sense of belonging. 
</P>
<P>
3 -- There's no need for a parent to explain the reason for demanding certain 
behavior. A command in itself should be sufficient. 
</P>
<P>
4 -- Children raised by traditional-style authoritarian parents are more likely 
to abuse drugs and alcohol as adults than children raised in other homes. 
</P>
<P>
5 -- Authoritarian and authoritative parents discipline in the same way. 
</P>
<P>
6 -- Basically, permissive parents are probably the best parents in terms of 
how their children develop. 
</P>
<P>
ANSWERS: 
</P>
<P>
1 -- FALSE. Consistency in discipline is important, and if a child discovers he 
can get away with something with one parent, but not with the other, or if 
their styles of discipline are totally different, the youngster will be 
confused. 
</P>
<P>
2 -- FALSE. It's all right for children to know that a parent is angry. Anger 
is an acceptable part of love, but children need to learn constructive outlets 
for anger. Parents and children need to learn to talk about their feelings with 
each other. 
</P>
<P>
3 -- FALSE. Parents who use the do-it-because-I-say-so discipline are 
authoritarian and their children don't learn how to think, analyze or make 
decisions on their own. They become followers rather than leaders. 
</P>
<P>
4 -- FALSE. Studies conducted by Berkeley psychologist Diana Baumrind revealed 
that while children raised by authoritarian parents were immature, showed poor 
self-esteem and weren't motivated to do well in school, they had a relatively 
low level of alcohol and drug abuse. 
</P>
<P>
5 -- FALSE. Authoritative parents take the time to explain the reasons for 
following certain commands, unlike authoritarian parents. They set limits of 
behavior, but they consider the child's point of view when setting limits. 
Children of authoritative parents, unlike children of permissive or 
authoritarian parents, are outstandingly well-adjusted, mature, happy, 
motivated, independent and socially adept. 
</P>
<P>
6 -- FALSE. The 12-year longitudinal Berkeley study revealed that the children 
who were worse off were those raised by permissive parents. Like those reared 
by rigid authoritarian parents, they had low self-esteem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA120689-0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 144583 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
December 6, 1989, Wednesday, Home Edition 
</P>
