<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
VIRGINIA; 
</P>
<P>
LAB WORKERS TEST NEGATIVE FOR VIRUS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hazleton Research Products, a Reston, Va., research laboratory where monkeys 
were found to be infected with a rare and deadly virus, said that precautionary 
testing found all of its employees to be free of the disease. The company sent 
workers' blood samples to the national Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta 
for analysis after one man who handled monkeys infected with the Ebola virus 
became ill and was placed in isolation at Fairfax Hospital. The disease, which 
has an incubation period of two to 21 days, causes internal and external 
bleeding and organ failure and has a 50% to 90% mortality rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
