<P>
Program Trading Activity Down Sharply: Program trading activity dropped sharply 
in the first two weeks of November after an outcry over the controversial 
strategy, which has been blamed for increasing market volatility, the New York 
Stock Exchange reported. A steep decline in index arbitrage, the main form of 
computerized program trading, reflected an exodus by large brokerages after the 
strategy was blamed by some for worsening a stock market drop on Oct. 13. Index 
arbitrage accounted for 38.7% of program trades from Nov. 6-10 and 25.7% from 
Nov. 13-17, down from 53.8% in October, the NYSE said. 
